Reading the Dataset on COVID-19 (coronavirus) vaccinations¶

country_vaccinations_df:</br>¶

Dataframe Names: cv_df, country_vaccinations_df</br>

Country-by-country data on global COVID-19 vaccinations.</br> This dataset includes international aggregates (World, continents, European Union…). They can be identified by their iso_code. This dataset consists of the following columns:</br>

  • country: name of the country (or region within a country).
  • iso_code: ISO 3166-1 alpha-3 – three-letter country codes.
  • date: date of the observation.
  • total_vaccinations: total number of doses administered and so on.
country_vaccinations_by_manufacturer_df:</br>¶

Dataframe Names: cvm_df, country_vaccinations_by_manufacturer_df</br>

This dataset includes European and American locations. They can be identified by their location.</br>

  • location: name of the country (or region within a country).
  • date: date of the observation.
  • vaccine: list of vaccines administered in the location.
  • total_vaccinations: total number of doses administered.

Which countries have the best vaccination progress?¶

Total COVID-19 Vaccinations Country-by-Country</br>¶

The Choropleth Map below shows the countries with total vaccinations. The countries that are purple are less vaccinated compared to the countries which are yellow/ brown. We find that China, India and United States some of the countries that has made the best vaccination progress.

People Vaccinated by COVID-19 Vaccine Country-by-Country</br>¶

The Choropleth Map below shows the countries that the total number of people who received at least one vaccine dose. If a person receives the first dose of a 2-dose vaccine, this metric goes up by 1. The countries that are dark blue/sky blue are less vaccinated compared to the countries which are dark red/brown. We find that India and United States some of the countries that has made the best vaccination progress.

The dataframe vac_df is used to store the group information based on the 'date', 'iso_code' and 'country' data to create a timeline_df dataframe to visualize the from 1st Jan to 13th May 2021 of the people who are vaccinated in this date range.

vac_df = cv_df.groupby(['date','iso_code','country']).sum().reset_index().sort_values('date', ascending=True).dropna()
mask = (vac_df['date'] > '2021-01-01') & (vac_df['date'] <= '2021-12-31')
vac_df['dt_str'] = vac_df['date'].apply(lambda x: x.strftime("%m/%d/%Y"))
timeline_df = vac_df.loc[mask]
timeline_df = timeline_df[timeline_df['daily_vaccinations']>0]

People Fully vaccinated by COVID-19 Vaccine Country-by-Country</br>¶

The Choropleth Map below shows the countries with total number of people who received all doses prescribed by the vaccination protocol. If a person receives the first dose of a 2-dose vaccine, this metric stays the same. If they receive the second dose, the metric goes up by 1. The countries like "India" is moderately vaccinated and "United States" made the best progress in vaccination. The white regions represent countries that does not have sufficient data.

top_5 = cv_df_grp.sort_values(by=['people_vaccinated'], ascending=False).head(5)

### Generate a Barplot
plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
people_vaccinated = sns.barplot(top_5['people_vaccinated'], top_5['country'], color = 'blue', label='people_vaccinated')
people_fully_vaccinated = sns.barplot(top_5['people_fully_vaccinated'], top_5['country'], color = 'green', label='people_fully_vaccinated')
### Add Texts for Barplots
for i,(value,name) in enumerate(zip(top_5['people_fully_vaccinated'],top_5['country'])):
    people_vaccinated.text(value,i-0.05,f'{value:,.0f}',size=10)
for i,(value,name) in enumerate(zip(top_5['people_vaccinated'],top_5['country'])):
    people_fully_vaccinated.text(value,i-0.05,f'{value:,.0f}',size=10)
plt.legend(loc=4)
plt.show()

How are the vaccination progress and the number of positive cases, deaths etc. linked in the United States?¶

State-by-state data on United States COVID-19 vaccinations and COVID-19 positive cases and deaths.¶

The file 'us_states_vaccination.xlsx' consists of the COVID-19 vaccination information of the different states of United States. The US states data mainly consists of the total number of doses administered and the daily number of doses administered to its citizens.

PreProcessing the Data for clustering¶

Here we are creating a new DataFrame object 'new_df' by grouping the data in 'Country_Vaccinations_data' by country.

To group the data based on country name and considering the features like "total_vaccinations','people_fully_vaccinated' and 'people_vaccinated',we are using the groupby and agggregation functions.

groupby('country') - groups the data based on country

agg.('columnname':'max - find the maximum value of respective column for each country.

Since when grouping the index will be by default set to the country name ,we are using the reset_index() function to reset the index to row numbers.

In [31]:
#columns = ['iso_code','country','vaccines','source_name','source_website','date']
#Data_for_clustering = Country_vaccinations_data.drop(columns,axis=1)
In [32]:
#grouping the data

new_df = Country_vaccinations_data.groupby('country').agg({'total_vaccinations':'max','people_fully_vaccinated':'max','people_vaccinated':'max'}).reset_index()

Since Country is a categorical column and it is of less significance when clustering data,the 'country' columns of 'new_df' is removed and the resulting dataframe is stored in 'df_clustering'.

In [33]:
df_clustering = new_df.drop('country',axis=1)

The dataframe contains many NAN and infinte values.In order to remove them we are using the function nan_to_num() of Numpy library,which will replace NAN and infinite values with 0's and finite values respectively.

The dataframe df_clustering is passed as an input to the function and the results are stored in a variable X,which will be used for identifying the Clusters

In [34]:
x  = pd.DataFrame(np.nan_to_num(df_clustering))

K-means Clustering algortihm is being used here and finding the ideal no.of clusters is an important task when using kmeans.

To find the best value for n_clusters we are creating a K-Means model for values of k (n_clusters) ranging from 2 to 11 and calculating the Silhoutte scores for each.

All these resulting Silhoutte scores are stored in a list 'silhouette_scores'.

In [35]:
silhouette_scores = []
for k in range(2, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    kmeans.fit(x)
    score = silhouette_score(x, kmeans.labels_)
    silhouette_scores.append(score)

Here we are potting the Silhoutte scores which have been obtained above ,to the best possible value for n_clusters.

plt.plot() i used to plot the data.

In [74]:
plt.plot(range(2, 11), silhouette_scores)
plt.xticks(range(2, 11))
plt.xlabel("Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Coefficient")
plt.show()

As shown in the above plot,we are getting the highest Silhoutte score for value k=2,i.e the Clustering is done properly when the number of clusters is 2.

So here,we are creating a K-Means model with number od clusters as 2.This model is used to fit the data,using the fit() fucntion.

The cluster labels which are results given by the K-Means model in variable kmeans.labels_,are stored in a new column 'cluster_labels' in the new_df dataframe.

In [37]:
#creating the K-Means model

kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2)
In [38]:
#fitting the data uisng the K-means model created

kmeans.fit(x)

# helper function
def plot_till_date(value1, value2, title, color1, color2) : 
    so_far_dict = {}
    
    for dates in country_vaccinations.date.unique() : 
        so_far_dict[dates], value1_count, value2_count = [], 0, 0
        #print(dates)
        for i in range(len(country_vaccinations)) : 
            if country_vaccinations.date[i] == dates : 
                value1_count += country_vaccinations[value1][i]
                value2_count += country_vaccinations[value2][i]
#         if dates not in so_far_dict.keys() : 
        so_far_dict[dates].append(value1_count) 
        so_far_dict[dates].append(value2_count)
    so_far_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(so_far_dict, orient = 'index', columns=[value1, value2])
    so_far_df.reset_index(inplace = True)
#     return so_far_df
    so_far_df.sort_values(by='index', inplace = True)
    plot = go.Figure(data=[go.Scatter( 
            x = so_far_df['index'], 
            y = so_far_df[value1], 
            stackgroup='one', 
            name = value1, 
            marker_color= color1), 
                           go.Scatter( 
            x = so_far_df['index'], 
            y = so_far_df[value2], 
            stackgroup='one',
            name = value2, 
            marker_color= color2) 
        ]) 
    plot.update_layout(
    title={
            'text' : title,
            'y':0.95,
            'x':0.5
        },
        xaxis_title="Date"
    )
    return plot.show()

#country_vaccinations.columns
plot_till_date('people_fully_vaccinated','people_vaccinated','People vaccinated vs Fully vaccinated till date', 'Red', 'Orange')
